Below is a possible workflow for your data analysis. It's mostly based on the Moving pictures tutorial. You are free to improve the analysis steps as you see fit. At any case, you should perform an ASV- and an OTU-based analysis and compare the results, and finally answer the research questions given in the PDFs "Fallstudie Vorbesprechung" and "Data analysis Vorbesprechung".

Sample metadata

Explore the sample metadata to familiarize yourself with the samples in detail. QIIME 2s metadata plugin provides a Visualizer called tabulate that generates a convenient view of a sample metadata file.

See the Qiime documentation for details on the metadata file format. You can validate the metadata table in Google Sheets using the Keemei plugin.

If you plan to share the Qiime result files with others, don't include confidential information (e.g. Personally Identifying Information, PII), in the metadata. Instead, encode it with variables that only authorized individuals have access to. For example, subject names should be replaced with anonymized subject identifiers before use with QIIME 2.

Obtaining and importing data

Data is imported in Qiime as QIIME 2 "artifacts". They are simply zip files that store data together with some QIIME 2-specific metadata, e.g. type and source of data. The metadata are tracked by Qiime automatically, which makes working with artifacts very convenient. Artifacts have the file extension .qza.

All QIIME 2 artifacts are assigned one artifact class, which indicates the semantics of the data (its "semantic type") and the file format that is used to store it inside of the .qza file. When you see artifacts (or inputs or outputs to an action) described with terms that look like Phylogeny[Rooted] or Phylogeny[Unrooted], that is the Artifact Class.

The file extension .qzv (QIIME Zipped Visualization) are files that store QIIME 2 Visualizations. QIIME 2 Visualizations represent data that are generated by QIIME 2 and intended to be viewed by humans, such as an interactive visualization.

Details on data import are given in the How-To: Import data for use with QIIME 2. Notably, the guide recommends importing demultiplexed data (as in your case) using a FASTQ "manifest" file, which is a simple text file that maps sample identifiers to one or two absolute filepaths pointing at .fastq.gz (or .fastq) files, depending on whether youre importing data from a single- or paried-end run.

Demultiplexing sequences

To reduce sequencing costs and increase the throughput, many samples are usually pooled together into one sequencing library ("multiplexing"). The samples are individually tagged using barcodes short, unique sequences ligated to each sample's DNA before pooling. This allows to sequence many samples at the same time and separate them computationally later ("demultiplexing").

The sequencing facility may perform demultiplexing itself, or it may give you one FASTQ file with all samples, and the barcodes still attached. In this case, you need to do the splitting/sorting the combined sequence data back into individual samples. Demultiplexing can be done via the demux plugin.

Even if you don't need this, its useful to generate a summary via qiime demux summarize. This allows to determine how many sequences were obtained per sample, and also to get a summary of the distribution of sequence qualities at each position in your sequence data.

Sequence quality control and feature table construction

Now you can generate the feature table. This is the central data matrix that quantifies the abundance of different microbial taxa found across all your individual samples.

ASV ID sample 1 sample 2 sample 3 ...
4jd8dv7a 0 17 82 ...
837sn2o0 1022 2430 9 ...
... ... ... ... ...
  • Rows: Unique biological "features" (OTUs or ASVs) identified from all sequences
  • Columns: Individual samples
  • Counts (frequencies): Numbers of this particular sequence ("feature") found in this sample

In Qiime, the output of this step is a

  • a FeatureTable[Frequency] QIIME 2 artifact, which contains counts (frequencies) of each unique sequence in each sample in the dataset, and
  • a FeatureData[Sequence] QIIME 2 artifact, which maps feature identifiers in the FeatureTable to the sequences they represent.

These are two of the most important artifact classes in a marker gene sequencing workflow, they are used for many downstream analyses (conceptual overview: feature table).

There are QIIME 2 plugins available for several quality control methods, including DADA2, Deblur, and basic quality-score-based filtering. Also, different algorithms can be interchangeably used to identify ASVs or cluster OTUs. The result is the same: A table of sequences and their counts.

  • DADA2 denoising can be done via the dada2 plugin (moving pictures tutorial). This quality control process will additionally filter any phiX reads (commonly present in marker gene Illumina sequence data) that are identified in the sequencing data, filter chimeric sequences, and merge paired end reads. Its the longest running step in your workflow.
  • OTU clustering can be done via the vsearch plugin (conceptual overview: denoising and clustering)

qiime dada2

To determine what values to pass for the parameters of the qiime dada2 denoise-* command, you should review the interactive quality plot tab in the demux.qzv file that was generated by qiime demux summarize above.

The denoising command qiime dada2 denoise-* (Qiime2 docs) does multiple different things that are discussed in detail in the DADA2 tutorial:

  1. Filter and trim
  2. Learn the error rates / Run sample inference algorithm
  3. Merge paired reads
  4. Construct sequence table
  5. Remove chimeras

qiime vsearch

OTU clustering is the traditional approach to quality control for amplicon datasets. It is described in an additional short Qiime2 tutorial. Even though the vsearch plugin docs say that the cluster-features-de-novo command "is not a general-purpose de novo clustering method, but rather is intended to be used for clustering the results of quality-filtering/dereplication methods like DADA2 (How-To: Clustering reads into OTUs), or for re-clustering a FeatureTable at a lower percent identity than it was originally clustered at", it can also be used for de-novo clustering.

FeatureTable and FeatureData summaries

After generating the feature table, youll want to explore the resulting data. Qiime lets you create visual summaries of the data via the feature-table plugin:

  • feature-table summarize how many sequences are associated with each sample and with each feature, histograms of those distributions, and some related summary statistics
  • feature-table tabulate-seqs provides a mapping of feature IDs to sequences, and links to easily BLAST each sequence against the NCBI nt database

Filtering features from the feature table

If you want, you can now filter out spurious sequences, that are observed in low counts and/or in only a few samples (Reitmeier et al. 2021). This is up to you.

Checking for contamination

This step is not part of the Moving pictures tutorial, but the process is described in detail on jordenrabasco.github.io.

Generate a tree for phylogenetic diversity analyses

Note that you don't need taxonomic annotation for the phylogenetic diversity analysis. Why is this? Taxonomy is a labeling system; phylogeny is a map of relatedness. You can build the phylogenetic tree directly from your sequence data, without ever needing to know the "names" of those sequences.

To generate a phylogenetic tree you can use the align-to-tree-mafft-fasttree pipeline from the phylogeny plugin.

  1. It uses mafft to perform a multiple sequence alignment (MSA) of the sequences in FeatureData[Sequence] to create a FeatureData[AlignedSequence] QIIME 2 artifact.
  2. Next, the pipeline masks (or filters) the alignment to remove highly variable (i.e. noisy) positions.
  3. Then, the pipeline applies FastTree to generate a phylogenetic tree from the masked alignment.
  4. FastTree creates an unrooted tree, so midpoint rooting is applied to place the root of the tree at the midpoint of the longest tip-to-tip distance in the unrooted tree.

[Additional information]

Taxonomy is a human-made labeling and organizational system for organisms. It gives organisms names and puts them into a hierarchical system of boxes (ranks) like Kingdom, Phylum, Class, Order, Family, Genus, and Species.

On the other hand, phylogeny is the study of evolutionary relationships among organisms. It describes how different species or groups are related to each other through common ancestors. It is a hypothesis about evolutionary history.

Alpha and beta diversity analysis

QIIME diversity analyses are available through the diversity plugin. It can compute alpha and beta diversity metrics, applies related statistical tests, and generates interactive visualizations.

For example, the core-metrics-phylogenetic method applies a collection of diversity metrics (both phylogenetic and non-phylogenetic) to a feature table (FeatureTable[Frequency] artifact).

An important parameter that you need to provide is the --p-sampling-depth parameter, which is the even sampling (i.e. rarefaction) depth. This allows to normalize for different sampling depths across different samples (Schloss 2024).

Alpha rarefaction plotting

To explore alpha diversity as a function of sampling depth you can use the qiime diversity alpha-rarefaction visualizer. This helps to determine if the richness of the samples has been fully observed or sequenced.

The bottom plot in the resulting visualization is important when grouping samples by metadata. It helps to ensure that the data presented in the top plot is reliable.

Taxonomic analysis

Of course it's also interesting to know "who is there". To explore the taxonomic composition of the samples, you need to assign taxonomy to the sequences in the FeatureData[Sequence] QIIME 2 artifact. You can do that using a pre-trained Naive Bayes classifier and the feature-classifier plugin using qiime feature-classifier classify-sklearn.

You can also train your own classifier based on the used primers, but the tutorial says that there are only minor differences relative to those trained on full-length sequences. The choice of the classifier is up to you.

You can then view the taxonomic composition of your samples with interactive bar plots generated with the qiime taxa barplot command.

The accuracy of the taxonomic assignment for 16S rRNA amplicons depends on the input data characteristics (e.g. sequence length, sequencing quality, and the specific variable region targeted, see e.g. Johnson et al. 2019, Hrovat et al. 2025), the reference database (quality and completeness), the methodology (choice of classification algorithm and its parameters like confidence thresholds, see e.g. Almeida et al. 2018), and the intrinsic biological limitations of the marker gene itself, which exhibits uneven evolutionary rates and thus possesses different resolving power across various phylogenetic clades.

Performance of RDP classifier (Nave Bayesian Classifier) for taxonomic assignment

This example shows the classification accuracy by query size (using leave-one-out testing). Numbers are percentages of tests correctly classified. This shows that accuracy is strongly dependent on sequence length and the taxonomic level of interest; e.g., for the 50-base segments was only 94.1% at the phylum level and decreased dramatically to 51.5% at the genus level. (Wang et al. 2007)

Differential abundance testing

To identify features that are differentially abundant (i.e. present in different abundances) across sample groups, you can use a tool like ANCOM-BC, which is implemented in the composition plugin.
